XI. PUBLIUS VALERIUS LAEVINUS AND PYRRHUS, KING OF EPIRUS.

Pyrrhus: the Greek word from which the name Pyrrhus is derived means ‘ re(l‚' ⁶ flame-colored'; hence Macaulay calls him ‘the recl king* With the story of Pyrrhus we reach the domain of historical truth. He was one of the greatest generals of antiquity‚ and one of the best kings. He was regarded by the Romans of later times with kindly feelings. Cicero refers to the war with Pyrrhus as ‘a struggle for dominion with a noble and powerful king,' and relates many anecdotes of his chivalrous conduct.
